__createIterableObject(), used in the numerous "generic iterables" tests, is defined as:

[1] Have to be enabled via harmony option

[2] Have to be enabled via "Experimental Web Platform Features" flag

[3] Flagged features have to be enabled via "Experimental Javascript features" flag

[4] Results are only applicable for the KHTML rendering engine.

[5] Flagged features have to be enabled via --harmony flag

[6] Available from Firefox 2 for code in a <script type="application/javascript;version=1.7"> (or version=1.8) tag.

[7] Available from Firefox 35 for code in a <script type="application/javascript;version=1.7"> (or version=1.8) tag.

[8] This compiler requires generic iterables have a Symbol.iterator or non-standard "@@iterator" method.

[9] Requires native support for Object.prototype.__proto__

[10] This compiler transforms extends into code that copies properties from the superclass, instead of using the prototype chain.

[11] Firefox doesn't allow a proxy's "get" handler to be triggered via the prototype chain, unless the proxied object does possess the named property (or the proxy's "has" handler reports it as present).

[12] From Firefox 18 up to 29, the getOwnPropertyDescriptor handler can only report non-existent properties if the proxy target is non-extensible rather than extensible

[13] Available from Firefox 18 up to 33 as the draft standard keys handler

[14] Note that prior to ES6, it was recommended that ES5 implementations forbid block-level declarations in strict mode.

[15] Available as the draft standard String.prototype.contains

[16] with is not supported in ejs

[17] Available from Firefox 17 up to 27 as the non-standard Array.prototype.iterator

[18] Available from Firefox 27 up to 35 as the non-standard Array.prototype["@@iterator"]

[19] Available as Array.prototype[Symbol.iterator]

[20] Available since Chrome 28

[21] Available since Firefox 26

[22] Note that this is distinct from the existence or functionality of Object.prototype.__proto__.
